# Visualization Rules

## When to Create a Visualization

Only create a diagram, graph, or visual when it is a clear 10/10 fit for the concept. A visualization must make something
significantly easier to understand than text alone. If the concept can be explained well with a code example, a list, or
a short paragraph - skip the visual entirely.

**Create a visual when:**

- There is a clear spatial relationship (architecture, data flow, request lifecycle)
- Multiple components interact in ways that are hard to follow in prose
- The reader needs to see the "big picture" at a glance
- Comparison of before/after, with/without is the core message

**Skip a visual when:**

- It just restates what the text already says
- It shows a simple linear sequence that a numbered list covers better
- The concept is straightforward and does not benefit from spatial layout
- You are unsure whether it helps - if in doubt, leave it out

## Diagram Variety

Do NOT default to timeline/sequence diagrams for everything. Choose the diagram type that best fits the concept:

| Concept | Best fit |
| --- | --- |
| Architecture / component relationships | Block diagram or flowchart |
| Data flow / request lifecycle | Flowchart with directional arrows |
| Comparison (before/after, with/without) | Side-by-side columns or table |
| Hierarchy / nesting (config layers, inheritance) | Tree diagram |
| Interaction between systems | Sequence diagram (only when timing matters) |
| State transitions | State machine diagram |
| Decision logic | Decision tree / branching flowchart |

Never force a timeline when the concept has no temporal dimension. Default to NO diagram and only add one when it
clearly earns its place.

## Quality Bar

Every visualization must be:

1. **Self-explanatory** - understandable without reading surrounding text
2. **Minimal** - no decorative elements, no redundant labels, no clutter
3. **Accurate** - matches the actual implementation, not a simplified fantasy
4. **Distinct** - adds information the text cannot convey as effectively
